1. Python (Core + Backend)
What they’ll test: depth, not syntax
Typical Questions:
Explain GIL in Python. When does it matter?
Difference between threading vs multiprocessing vs async (asyncio)?
How do you optimize a slow API in Python?
What are decorators? Use case in real projects?
How does memory management / garbage collection work?
What interviewer expects:
Clear understanding of concurrency trade-offs
Practical answers (e.g., “used async for IO-bound APIs”)
Not textbook definitions
🔹 2. JavaScript / TypeScript (Moderate Depth)
Typical Questions:
Difference between TypeScript vs JavaScript
Explain event loop, promises, async/await
What is closure?
How do you handle API errors in frontend/backend integration?
Expected:
Basic working knowledge (not frontend expert level)
Ability to integrate with backend APIs
🔹 3. API & Backend Architecture (VERY IMPORTANT)
This is where most candidates fail.
Questions:
Design a scalable REST API
What is idempotency?
Difference between REST vs JSON-RPC
How do you handle rate limiting & retries?
How do you secure APIs?
Must include in answers:
Authentication (OAuth 2.1, JWT)
Logging + monitoring
Caching (Redis)
API versioning
🔹 4. Microservices & System Design
Questions:
Design a microservice for AI query processing
How do services communicate? (REST, queues, events)
How do you ensure fault tolerance?
What is circuit breaker pattern?
Expected:
Understanding of:
Service separation
Load balancing
Message queues (Kafka/RabbitMQ basics)
🔹 5. LLM / AI / RAG (CRITICAL SECTION)
This is the main differentiator.
Questions:
What is an LLM? How does it work?
What is RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation)?
How do you reduce hallucination?
What are embeddings?
How would you design a chatbot using LLM + database?
What is agentic AI?
Strong Answer Should Include:
LLM = transformer-based model
RAG = retrieval + generation pipeline
Vector DB (FAISS, Pinecone, etc.)
Prompt engineering basics
Context injection
🔹 6. MCP Servers / AI Integration (Advanced but expected)
Since JD mentions this explicitly.
Questions:
What is MCP (Model Context Protocol)? (if known)
How do you expose tools to AI agents?
How do you ensure secure tool execution?
Expected:
Even if MCP unknown → candidate should relate to:
API-based tool calling
Function calling (OpenAI-style)
Secure execution sandboxing
🔹 7. Authentication & Security
Questions:
Explain OAuth 2.0 / 2.1 flow
What is JWT?
How do you secure AI APIs?
Expected:
Token-based auth
Role-based access control
API gateway usage
🔹 8. Git, Testing & Debugging
Questions:
Git workflow (branching strategy)
Difference between unit vs integration testing
How do you debug a production issue?
Expected:
Practical answers (logs, tracing, rollback)
🔹 9. Scenario-Based Questions (VERY COMMON)
These decide selection.
Examples:
“User query is slow in AI system—how will you debug?”
“LLM giving wrong answers—what will you do?”
“Design AI agent that fetches data from multiple APIs”
Strong approach:
Break problem → identify bottleneck → propose solution
🔹 10. Coding Round (Python likely)
Examples:
API-based coding problem
String/data processing
Basic DSA (medium level)
🔥 What Gets Candidates SELECTED
Tell your candidates to focus on:
✔ Real project explanation (very important)
✔ Clear understanding of RAG + APIs
✔ Ability to explain architecture simply
✔ Confidence in Python + backend design
❌ Common Rejection Reasons
Only theoretical AI knowledge (no implementation)
Weak backend fundamentals
No clarity on RAG / LLM flow
Poor communication
